Bring a large #saucepan of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}. When boiling, add the @linguine{180%grams} to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%mins}.

Once the pasta is cooked, drain in a #colander and pop back in the pan. Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

While the pasta cooks, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Drain the @king prawns{150%grams}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Once the oil is hot, add the prawns and @diced chorizo{60%grams} to the #pan and fry until the prawns are almost cooked through, ~{3-4%mins}.

Next, add the garlic and stir-fry for ~{30%secs}.

  Stir the @chicken stock paste{10%grams}, @double cream{150%grams} and @water for the sauce{75%milliliters} into the pan. Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the sauce has thickened, stir in the @peas{120%grams} and the @grated hard Italian style cheese{20%grams}. Cook until the peas are piping hot, ~{1-2%mins}.

Stir in the cooked pasta. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of @water{} if it's a little too thick.

Share the creamy prawn and chorizo linguine between your #bowls{}. Top with a handful of @wild rocket{20%grams} and drizzle over the @balsamic glaze{12%milliliters} to finish. Enjoy!